<h2>3. How your solar system works</h2>
<p>In simple terms:</p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Sunlight</strong> hits the solar panels on your roof.</li>
<li>The panels convert sunlight into <strong>DC electricity</strong> (the same kind that comes out of a battery).</li>
<li>The <strong>inverter</strong> converts DC into <strong>AC electricity</strong> (the kind your house uses).</li>
<li>AC power flows first to <strong>your house</strong> &mdash; running your appliances directly.</li>
<li>Any leftover power is <strong>exported to the grid</strong> through your meter, earning you a feed-in credit.</li>
<li>When the sun isn't shining, your house draws power from the grid normally.</li>
</ol>
<p>If you have a battery, surplus solar charges the battery first (during the day) and discharges it back into your home in the evening &mdash; reducing what you import from the grid.</p>
<p><strong>Important:</strong> solar panels only work when there is daylight. They produce most power on clear sunny days, less on overcast days, and very little at dawn, dusk or in rain. They do not work at night.</p>

<h2>4. Your components</h2>
<h3>Solar panels</h3>
<p>Your panels are <span class="fill">[BRAND] [MODEL]</span>, rated at <span class="fill">[W]</span> watts each. They have an expected service life of 25+ years and carry a product warranty of <span class="fill">[YEARS]</span> years and a performance warranty of <span class="fill">[YEARS]</span> years (output guaranteed above <span class="fill">[%]</span> at 25 years). The panel datasheet is included as Appendix A.</p>

<h3>Inverter</h3>
<p>Your inverter is a <span class="fill">[BRAND] [MODEL]</span>, serial number <span class="fill">[SN]</span>. It is mounted <span class="fill">[LOCATION &mdash; e.g. on the south wall of the garage, in the meter box, in the roof cavity]</span>. The inverter has a product warranty of <span class="fill">[YEARS]</span> years. The inverter manual is included as Appendix B.</p>
<div class="note">The inverter is the part of your system most likely to need attention over its lifetime. It is also the part that shows you what the system is doing &mdash; through its LED indicators, screen, or connected app.</div>

<h3>DC isolator (rooftop)</h3>
<p>A weatherproof DC isolator is mounted on the roof near the panel array. This disconnects the panels from the inverter and is operated by emergency services if needed. <strong>Do not operate this isolator yourself</strong> &mdash; opening it under load can cause arcing.</p>

<h3>DC isolator (inverter)</h3>
<p>A second DC isolator sits next to the inverter. Same rule &mdash; do not operate under load.</p>

<h3>AC isolator</h3>
<p>The AC isolator sits between the inverter and your switchboard. This is the isolator you may need to operate in an emergency (see Section 10). It is located <span class="fill">[LOCATION]</span>.</p>

<h3>Monitoring</h3>
<p>Your inverter is connected to your home Wi-Fi and reports generation data to your installer's portal in real time. The portal is accessible at <span class="fill">[PORTAL URL]</span> using the PIN provided at handover. The inverter manufacturer may also provide its own app &mdash; details in Appendix B.</p>

<h2>5. Daily operation &mdash; what to expect</h2>
<p>Once commissioned, your system runs automatically. You do not need to switch it on each morning or off at night &mdash; the inverter does this itself when the panel voltage rises and falls with the sun.</p>

<h3>A normal day</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>5:30&ndash;7:00 AM</strong> &mdash; system wakes up as light hits the panels. Output is low.</li>
<li><strong>9:00 AM &ndash; 3:00 PM</strong> &mdash; peak production. Most of your daily generation happens here.</li>
<li><strong>3:00&ndash;6:30 PM</strong> &mdash; output tapers off.</li>
<li><strong>After sunset</strong> &mdash; inverter goes to standby (LED may dim or change colour). No generation overnight.</li>
</ul>

<h3>What affects output</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Factor</th><th>Impact</th></tr>
<tr><td>Cloud cover</td><td>Light cloud: 60&ndash;80% of clear-sky output. Heavy cloud: 10&ndash;30%.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Rain</td><td>Reduces output, but cleans the panels.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Season</td><td>Summer days produce roughly 2x what winter days produce, due to sun angle and day length.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Heat</td><td>Panels lose ~0.3&ndash;0.4% efficiency per &deg;C above 25&deg;C. A 40&deg;C day produces less than a 25&deg;C day, even with the same sun.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Dust / pollen</td><td>Light soiling: 1&ndash;3% loss. Heavy soiling (bushfire ash, salt spray): up to 25%.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Shade</td><td>Even partial shade on one panel can disproportionately reduce string output if optimisers are not fitted.</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>6. Reading your inverter</h2>
<p>Your inverter <span class="fill">[has / does not have]</span> a screen. The status indicators mean:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Indicator</th><th>Meaning</th><th>Action</th></tr>
<tr><td>Solid green</td><td>Normal operation &mdash; generating</td><td>Nothing &mdash; all good</td></tr>
<tr><td>Slow green flash</td><td>Standby (night or early morning)</td><td>Nothing &mdash; will resume at sunrise</td></tr>
<tr><td>Solid orange / yellow</td><td>Reduced output (heat or grid issue)</td><td>Note the time; check again next clear day</td></tr>
<tr><td>Flashing red</td><td>Fault detected</td><td>See Section 11. Note any code shown.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Solid red</td><td>System tripped/stopped</td><td>Do not reset more than once. Call installer.</td></tr>
<tr><td>No lights at all</td><td>Inverter has no power</td><td>Check AC isolator is on. If on, call installer.</td></tr>
</table>
<p>Refer to Appendix B (inverter manual) for codes specific to your model.</p>

<h2>7. Monitoring your system</h2>
<p>You have two ways to see what your system is doing:</p>
<h3>Customer portal</h3>
<p>Visit <span class="fill">[PORTAL URL]</span> and sign in with your PIN. The portal shows live generation, monthly and lifetime totals, dollar savings, CO&#8322; offset, and any performance alerts. See the separate <strong>Customer Guide</strong> for full portal instructions.</p>

<h3>Manufacturer app (optional)</h3>
<p>Your inverter manufacturer also provides a free app: <span class="fill">[APP NAME &amp; STORE LINK]</span>. This gives you more technical detail (per-string output, voltage, temperature). The login is configured during commissioning &mdash; your credentials are <span class="fill">[USERNAME / starter password / "see appendix"]</span>.</p>

<div class="note">If the inverter loses Wi-Fi, the portal will show "no recent data". The inverter keeps generating &mdash; it just can't tell anyone. Check your home router; reconnect the inverter using the procedure in Appendix B.</div>

<h2>8. Maintenance schedule</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Interval</th><th>Task</th><th>Who</th></tr>
<tr><td>Monthly</td><td>Visual check from the ground &mdash; panels look intact, no new shading from tree growth, inverter LED is normal</td><td>You</td></tr>
<tr><td>Quarterly</td><td>Glance at portal to confirm generation is in the expected range for the season</td><td>You</td></tr>
<tr><td>Annually</td><td>Visual safety inspection (every 12 months &mdash; included with most installers)</td><td>Installer</td></tr>
<tr><td>Every 3&ndash;5 years (or sooner in heavy dust / salt / bird areas)</td><td>Professional panel clean</td><td>Installer or licensed cleaner</td></tr>
<tr><td>Every 5 years</td><td>Full electrical safety test (string test, IR scan, isolator check)</td><td>Licensed electrician</td></tr>
<tr><td>Every 10 years</td><td>Inverter check / replacement consideration (many inverters last 10&ndash;15 years)</td><td>Installer</td></tr>
</table>

<h2>9. Cleaning your panels</h2>
<p>Most panels are self-cleaning to a useful degree &mdash; rain washes off most dust. However, in coastal, dusty or heavily treed areas, a professional clean every 3&ndash;5 years can recover 5&ndash;15% of lost output.</p>

<h3>If you choose to DIY clean (ground level only)</h3>
<ul>
<li><strong>Never climb on the roof.</strong> Falls from height are the most common cause of solar-related injury. Use a long-reach soft brush from the ground only.</li>
<li>Clean in the early morning or late afternoon &mdash; never on a hot panel, which can crack from thermal shock when cold water hits.</li>
<li>Use lukewarm water and a soft brush. <strong>Do not use detergent, high-pressure washers, or abrasive cleaners</strong> &mdash; these void the panel warranty.</li>
<li>Avoid walking on panels under any circumstances &mdash; even a hairline crack can destroy a panel's output and may not be visible to the eye.</li>
</ul>
<div class="warning">If your panels are on a two-storey roof, a steep-pitch roof, or you cannot reach safely from the ground, <strong>book a professional clean</strong>. The cost (typically $200&ndash;$350) is far less than the cost of falling off a roof.</div>

<h2>10. Safety &mdash; isolators &amp; emergency procedures</h2>

<h3>Knowing your isolators</h3>
<table>
<tr><th>Isolator</th><th>Location</th><th>Operate yourself?</th></tr>
<tr><td>DC rooftop isolator</td><td>On the roof near the panel array</td><td>No &mdash; emergency services only</td></tr>
<tr><td>DC inverter isolator</td><td>Next to inverter</td><td>No &mdash; licensed electrician only</td></tr>
<tr><td>AC isolator</td><td><span class="fill">[LOCATION]</span></td><td>Yes &mdash; in emergencies (see below)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Main switch (solar supply)</td><td>In switchboard, labelled "Solar Supply Main Switch"</td><td>Yes &mdash; in emergencies</td></tr>
</table>

<h3>Emergency procedures</h3>
<div class="danger">
<strong>If you see sparks, smoke, fire, or smell burning from the inverter or any solar wiring:</strong>
<ol>
<li>Turn off the <strong>AC isolator</strong> and the <strong>Solar Supply Main Switch</strong> in your switchboard.</li>
<li>Do <strong>not</strong> try to open the DC isolators &mdash; opening them under load can ignite an arc.</li>
<li>Evacuate the building if there is any smoke or fire. Call <strong>000</strong>.</li>
<li>Tell the attending fire service: "Solar PV on roof, DC isolator on roof, AC isolator is off." Show them this manual if you can.</li>
<li>After it's safe, call your installer on the number in Section 19.</li>
</ol>
</div>

<h3>Storm, hail, fallen tree</h3>
<ul>
<li>If panels are visibly damaged: turn off the AC isolator. Stay clear of the area. Call your installer.</li>
<li>Photograph damage from the ground (do not climb). You'll need photos for insurance.</li>
<li>Do not touch any cables that may have come loose.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Water ingress around inverter</h3>
<ul>
<li>Turn off AC isolator immediately. Do not touch the inverter.</li>
<li>Call your installer. Do not attempt to dry the unit yourself.</li>
</ul>

<h3>You smell something funny but everything looks fine</h3>
<ul>
<li>Trust your nose. Turn off AC isolator. Call your installer the same day.</li>
<li>Electrical fires can smoulder for hours before flaring &mdash; never "wait and see" with electrical smells.</li>
</ul>

<h2>11. Fault codes &amp; common issues</h2>
<p>Common issues you might see, in plain language:</p>
<table>
<tr><th>Symptom</th><th>Likely cause</th><th>What to do</th></tr>
<tr><td>"No production today" message in portal</td><td>Wi-Fi disconnected, or grid outage, or inverter fault</td><td>Check inverter LED. If green, it's likely Wi-Fi. If red, call installer.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Generation suddenly half what it was</td><td>One string offline, partial shading, soiling</td><td>Check portal for per-string data. Book a diagnostic if persistent.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inverter trips off in middle of sunny days</td><td>Grid over-voltage in your area (very common in solar-dense suburbs)</td><td>Not your fault &mdash; report to installer. They notify the distributor.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inverter LED flashes red briefly then resets</td><td>Brief grid disturbance &mdash; harmless if rare</td><td>Note it. If it happens daily, call installer.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Fan noise from inverter on hot days</td><td>Normal &mdash; inverter is cooling itself</td><td>Nothing &mdash; that's how it should work.</td></tr>
<tr><td>Loud buzzing or clicking from inverter</td><td>Not normal</td><td>Turn off AC isolator. Call installer.</td></tr>
</table>
<p>For manufacturer-specific fault codes, see Appendix B. Always note the exact code shown before resetting anything.</p>

<h2>12. Battery (if installed)</h2>
<div class="tplnote"><strong>DELETE this whole section if the customer has no battery.</strong></div>

<p>Your battery is a <span class="fill">[BRAND] [MODEL]</span>, capacity <span class="fill">[X.X] kWh</span> (useable). It is mounted <span class="fill">[LOCATION]</span>.</p>

<h3>How it works</h3>
<p>During the day, when your solar produces more than your home uses, the surplus charges the battery instead of being exported. In the evening, when solar stops, the battery discharges to power your home &mdash; reducing what you import from the grid. The whole process is automatic.</p>

<h3>Backup mode</h3>
<p>Your battery <span class="fill">[is / is not]</span> configured for backup. If configured for backup, during a grid outage the battery will continue to power <span class="fill">[the whole home / essential circuits only]</span>. Backup behaviour is governed by the changeover switch installed during commissioning. See your inverter manual for the indicator that shows "running on battery".</p>

<h3>Battery care</h3>
<ul>
<li>Do not block the battery's vents or stack items on it.</li>
<li>Keep the area around the battery clear of flammable items (1 m exclusion zone per AS/NZS 5139).</li>
<li>Do not attempt to open the battery enclosure under any circumstances &mdash; lithium fires are extremely difficult to extinguish.</li>
<li>If you see smoke, hear hissing, or smell a sweet/chemical odour from the battery &mdash; evacuate and call <strong>000</strong>. Lithium battery fires can re-ignite hours later.</li>
</ul>

<h3>Battery warranty</h3>
<p>Your battery is warranted for <span class="fill">[YEARS]</span> years or <span class="fill">[CYCLES]</span> full cycles, whichever comes first, with end-of-warranty capacity guaranteed at <span class="fill">[%]</span> of original. Warranty documents are in Appendix C.</p>

<h2>13. Warranties</h2>
<table>
<tr><th>Component</th><th>Product warranty</th><th>Performance warranty</th><th>Held by</th></tr>
<tr><td>Solar panels</td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS]</span></td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS] @ [%]</span></td><td>Manufacturer (via installer)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inverter</td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS]</span></td><td>N/A</td><td>Manufacturer (via installer)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Battery</td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS] / [CYCLES]</span></td><td><span class="fill">[%] at end</span></td><td>Manufacturer (via installer)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Mounting system</td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS]</span></td><td>N/A</td><td>Manufacturer (via installer)</td></tr>
<tr><td>Installation workmanship</td><td>5 years minimum (CEC Code)</td><td>N/A</td><td><span class="fill">[INSTALLER COMPANY NAME]</span></td></tr>
<tr><td>Whole-of-system performance</td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS, if offered]</span></td><td><span class="fill">[YEARS]</span></td><td><span class="fill">[INSTALLER COMPANY NAME]</span></td></tr>
</table>

<h3>How to claim</h3>
<ol>
<li>Open the customer portal &rarr; <strong>My System &rarr; Components</strong>, find the affected component, tap <strong>Start warranty claim</strong>.</li>
<li>Describe the issue. Attach photos and the fault code if any.</li>
<li>Your installer handles the manufacturer paperwork on your behalf at no charge.</li>
<li>If the claim is approved, repair or replacement is arranged. If declined, you receive a written reason.</li>
</ol>
<div class="warning"><strong>Things that void warranty:</strong> walking on panels, using high-pressure cleaners or detergents on panels, unauthorised modifications to the system, damage from neglect (e.g. tree-growth shading you were warned about and didn't act on), damage from pest entry where the system was certified pest-proof at commissioning.</div>

<h2>14. Insurance</h2>
<p>Notify your home insurer that you have a solar PV system. Many require this in writing. Premium changes are typically modest (~$30&ndash;$80/yr) but failing to declare the system can void the entire policy.</p>
<p>What to tell your insurer:</p>
<ul>
<li>System size in kW (DC and AC)</li>
<li>Install date and installer details</li>
<li>That the system is CEC-compliant and installed by a CEC-accredited installer</li>
<li>Whether you have a battery, and if so, its make/model/capacity</li>
</ul>
<p>Your customer portal contains an <strong>Insurance Documentation Pack</strong> button under Documents &mdash; this generates a single PDF you can email straight to your insurer.</p>

<h2>15. STC rebate &amp; tax records</h2>
<p>Your system was eligible for <span class="fill">[N]</span> Small-scale Technology Certificates (STCs) under the federal Renewable Energy Target. <span class="fill">[INSTALLER COMPANY NAME]</span> claimed these on your behalf and discounted <strong>$<span class="fill">[AMOUNT]</span></strong> off your invoice.</p>
<p>You do not need to do anything further &mdash; the STC has been assigned, traded and accounted for. Keep this manual and your final invoice for tax records (especially if you are claiming the system as part of an investment property or business). For owner-occupiers, no tax declaration is required.</p>

<h2>16. Adding to your system</h2>
<p>You can add to your system over time. Before you do, check with your installer &mdash; some additions require network approval (re-application to your distributor) and may take 4&ndash;8 weeks.</p>

<table>
<tr><th>Addition</th><th>Network approval needed?</th><th>Typical lead time</th></tr>
<tr><td>Panel cleaning, performance test</td><td>No</td><td>1&ndash;2 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td>Like-for-like inverter replacement (same brand, same size)</td><td>No</td><td>1&ndash;2 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td>Inverter upgrade (different brand or larger)</td><td>Yes</td><td>4&ndash;8 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td>Add a battery</td><td>Yes (for grid-connect)</td><td>4&ndash;8 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td>Add more panels (system size increase)</td><td>Yes</td><td>4&ndash;8 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td>EV charger</td><td>Sometimes (depends on supply)</td><td>2&ndash;4 weeks</td></tr>
<tr><td>Hot water diverter</td><td>No</td><td>1&ndash;2 weeks</td></tr>
</table>
<div class="warning"><strong>QLD Solar Bonus Scheme customers (44&cent;/kWh tariff):</strong> adding a battery, increasing system size, or upgrading the inverter to a higher-rated unit will <strong>permanently void</strong> your 44&cent; feed-in tariff. The new rate would drop to 6&ndash;10&cent;/kWh &mdash; a typical loss of $1,400&ndash;$1,600 per year. Discuss with your installer first.</div>

<h2>17. Selling your home</h2>
<p>Solar systems transfer to the new owner with the house. The 25-year panel warranty, the inverter warranty, the battery warranty and the installer workmanship warranty all transfer automatically &mdash; <strong>they are tied to the property, not to you</strong>.</p>

<h3>At settlement, give the buyer:</h3>
<ul>
<li>This manual</li>
<li>The Grid-Connect Owner's Manual (if grid-connected)</li>
<li>Final commissioning paperwork (CES certificate, COES, SAA)</li>
<li>The customer portal access details (your installer will transfer the account on request)</li>
<li>The most recent annual inspection report, if any</li>
</ul>

<h3>Notify</h3>
<ul>
<li>Your installer &mdash; they'll transfer the portal account and warranty records to the new owner</li>
<li>Your electricity retailer &mdash; cancel the final-resident export agreement; the new owner sets up theirs</li>
<li>Your insurer &mdash; cancel the policy on settlement day</li>
</ul>

<h2>18. End-of-life &amp; disposal</h2>
<p>Solar panels are recyclable. At end-of-life (25+ years) or if a panel is damaged:</p>
<ul>
<li>Do not put panels in household waste &mdash; they contain glass, aluminium and small amounts of silver and lead.</li>
<li>Contact your installer or a CEC-accredited recycler. Many councils now offer drop-off points.</li>
<li>Batteries <strong>must</strong> be returned to a licensed lithium-battery recycler &mdash; never to general waste or scrap metal. Battery fires in landfill are a serious problem.</li>
<li>Inverters can usually be returned to the manufacturer or to e-waste recycling.</li>
</ul>

