<h2>20. Glossary</h2>
<ul>
<li><strong>AC (alternating current)</strong> &mdash; the type of electricity used in your home and on the grid.</li>
<li><strong>AS/NZS 5033</strong> &mdash; Australian/New Zealand standard for the installation of PV arrays.</li>
<li><strong>CEC</strong> &mdash; Clean Energy Council. The industry body that accredits installers and sets the code of conduct.</li>
<li><strong>CES / COES</strong> &mdash; Certificate of Electrical Safety. Issued by the electrician at install completion.</li>
<li><strong>DC (direct current)</strong> &mdash; the type of electricity solar panels produce. Converted to AC by the inverter.</li>
<li><strong>DNSP</strong> &mdash; Distribution Network Service Provider. The company that owns and maintains the poles and wires in your street. Different to your retailer.</li>
<li><strong>Feed-in tariff (FiT)</strong> &mdash; the per-kWh rate your retailer pays for solar energy you export to the grid.</li>
<li><strong>Inverter</strong> &mdash; converts DC from the panels into AC for your home.</li>
<li><strong>kW vs kWh</strong> &mdash; kW is power (rate); kWh is energy (amount). A 6 kW system running flat-out for one hour produces 6 kWh.</li>
<li><strong>SAA</strong> &mdash; Solar Accreditation Australia. (Formerly CEC accreditation.)</li>
<li><strong>STC</strong> &mdash; Small-scale Technology Certificate. Federal subsidy claimed by your installer at install and discounted off your invoice.</li>
<li><strong>String</strong> &mdash; a series-connected group of panels wired to one input of the inverter. Most home systems have 1&ndash;3 strings.</li>
<li><strong>VPP</strong> &mdash; Virtual Power Plant. A program (typically by a retailer) that orchestrates many home batteries to act like a single grid-scale generator. You're paid to participate.</li>
</ul>

<h2>21. Quick reference card</h2>
<div class="note">
<strong>If something looks wrong:</strong>
<ol>
<li>Check inverter LED &mdash; green = OK, orange = reduced, red = fault.</li>
<li>Open the customer portal &mdash; check for an alert or message.</li>
<li>Note the fault code (if any).</li>
<li>Message your installer through the portal, or call <span class="fill">[INSTALLER PHONE]</span>.</li>
</ol>
<strong>In an emergency:</strong>
<ol>
<li>Turn off AC isolator (<span class="fill">[LOCATION]</span>).</li>
<li>Turn off Solar Supply Main Switch in switchboard.</li>
<li>Call 000 if fire/smoke.</li>
<li>Call <span class="fill">[INSTALLER AFTER-HOURS PHONE]</span>.</li>
</ol>
</div>

